@label{GC-API: @subsection{Controlling Garbage Collection}}

Lua uses two numbers to control its garbage collection:
the @emph{count} and the @emph{threshold} @see{GC}.
The first counts the amount of memory in use by Lua;
when the count reaches the threshold,
Lua runs its garbage collector.
After the collection, the count is updated
and the threshold  is set to twice the count value.

You can access the current values of these two numbers through the
following functions:
@verbatim{
       int  lua_getgccount     (lua_State *L);
       int  lua_getgcthreshold (lua_State *L);
}
@DefAPI{lua_getgcthreshold} @DefAPI{lua_getgccount}
Both return their respective values in Kbytes.
You can change the threshold value with
@verbatim{
       void  lua_setgcthreshold (lua_State *L, int newthreshold);
}
@DefAPI{lua_setgcthreshold}
Again, the @T{newthreshold} value is given in Kbytes.
When you call this function,
Lua sets the new threshold and checks it against the byte counter.
If the new threshold is less than the byte counter,
then Lua immediately runs the garbage collector.
In particular
@T{lua_setgcthreshold(L,0)} forces a garbage collection.
After the collection,
a new threshold is set according to the previous rule.


@label{userdata: @subsection{Userdata}}

Userdata represents C values in Lua.
Lua supports two types of userdata:
@Def{full userdata} and @Def{light userdata}.

A full userdata represents a block of memory.
It is an object (like a table):
You must create it, it can have its own metatable,
and you can detect when it is being collected.
A full userdata is only equal to itself (under raw equality).

A light userdata represents a pointer.
It is a value (like a number):
You do not create it, it has no metatables,
it is not collected (as it was never created).
A light userdata is equal to @Q{any}
light userdata with the same C address.

In Lua code, there is no way to test whether a userdata is full or light;
both have type @T{userdata}.
In C code, @T{lua_type} returns @T{LUA_TUSERDATA} for full userdata,
and @T{LUA_TLIGHTUSERDATA} for light userdata.

You can create a new full userdata with the following function:
@verbatim{
       void *lua_newuserdata (lua_State *L, size_t size);
}
@DefAPI{lua_newuserdata}
This function allocates a new block of memory with the given size,
pushes on the stack a new userdata with the block address,
and returns this address.

To push a light userdata into the stack you use
@T{lua_pushlightuserdata} @see{pushing}.

@T{lua_touserdata} @see{lua-to} retrieves the value of a userdata.
When applied on a full userdata, it returns the address of its block;
when applied on a light userdata, it returns its pointer;
when applied on a non-userdata value, it returns @T{NULL}.

When Lua collects a full userdata,
it calls the userdata's @T{gc} metamethod, if any,
and then it frees the userdata's corresponding memory.


@subsection{Metatables}

The following functions allow you to manipulate the metatables
of an object:
@verbatim{
       int lua_getmetatable (lua_State *L, int index);
       int lua_setmetatable (lua_State *L, int index);
}
@IndexAPI{lua_getmetatable} pushes on the stack
the metatable of a given object.
If the index is not valid,
or if the object does not have a metatable,
@IndexAPI{lua_getmetatable} returns 0 and pushes nothing on the stack.

@T{lua_setmetatable} pops a table from the stack and
sets it as the new metatable for the given object.


@subsection{Loading Lua Chunks}

You can load a Lua chunk with @IndexAPI{lua_load}:
@verbatim{
       typedef const char * (*lua_Chunkreader)
                                (lua_State *L, void *data, size_t *size);

       int lua_load (lua_State *L, lua_Chunkreader reader, void *data,
                                   const char *chunkname);
}
@DefAPI{Chunkreader}
The return values of @T{lua_load} are:
@itemize{
@item 0 @Em no errors;
@item @IndexAPI{LUA_ERRSYNTAX} @Em{}
syntax error during pre-compilation.
@item @IndexAPI{LUA_ERRMEM} @Em{}
memory allocation error.
}
If there are no errors,
@T{lua_load} pushes the compiled chunk as a Lua
function on top of the stack.
Otherwise, it pushes an error message.

@T{lua_load} automatically detects whether the chunk is text or binary,
and loads it accordingly (see program @IndexVerb{luac}).

@T{lua_load} uses a user-supplied
@emph{reader} function to read the chunk.
Every time it needs another piece of the chunk,
@T{lua_load} calls the reader,
passing along its @T{data} parameter.
The reader must return a pointer to a block of memory
with a new piece of the chunk
and set @T{size} to the block size.
To signal the end of the chunk, the reader returns @T{NULL}.
The reader function may return pieces of any size greater than zero.

The @emph{chunkname} is used for error messages
and debug information @see{debugI}.

See the auxiliary library (@T{lauxlib.c})
for examples of how to use @T{lua_load}
and for some ready-to-use functions to load chunks
from files and strings.


@subsection{Manipulating Tables}

Tables are created by calling
the function
@verbatim{
       void lua_createtable (lua_State *L, int narr, int nrec);
}
@DefAPI{lua_createtable}
This function creates a new empty table and pushes it onto the stack.
The new table has space pre-allocated
for @T{narr} array elements plus @T{nrec} non-array elements.
This pre-allocation is useful when you know exactly how many elements
the table will have.
Otherwise you can use the macro @IndexAPI{lua_newtable}:
@verbatim{
#define lua_newtable(L) lua_createtable(L, 0, 0)
}

To read a value from a table that resides somewhere in the stack,
call
@verbatim{
       void lua_gettable (lua_State *L, int index);
}
@DefAPI{lua_gettable}
where @T{index} points to the table.
@T{lua_gettable} pops a key from the stack
and returns (on the stack) the contents of the table at that key.
The table is left where it was in the stack.
As in Lua, this function may trigger a metamethod
for the @Q{index} event @see{metatable}.
To get the real value of any table key,
without invoking any metamethod,
use the @emph{raw} version:
@verbatim{
       void lua_rawget (lua_State *L, int index);
}
@DefAPI{lua_rawget}

To store a value into a table that resides somewhere in the stack,
you push the key and then the value onto the stack,
and call
@verbatim{
       void lua_settable (lua_State *L, int index);
}
@DefAPI{lua_settable}
where @T{index} points to the table.
@T{lua_settable} pops from the stack both the key and the value.
The table is left where it was in the stack.
As in Lua, this operation may trigger a metamethod
for the @Q{settable} or @Q{newindex} events.
To set the real value of any table index,
without invoking any metamethod,
use the @emph{raw} version:
@verbatim{
       void lua_rawset (lua_State *L, int index);
}
@DefAPI{lua_rawset}

You can traverse a table with the function
@verbatim{
       int lua_next (lua_State *L, int index);
}
@DefAPI{lua_next}
where @T{index} points to the table to be traversed.
The function pops a key from the stack,
and pushes a key-value pair from the table
(the @Q{next} pair after the given key).
If there are no more elements, then @T{lua_next} returns 0
(and pushes nothing).
Use a @nil key to signal the start of a traversal.

A typical traversal looks like this:
@verbatim{
       /* table is in the stack at index `t' */
       lua_pushnil(L);  /* first key */
       while (lua_next(L, t) != 0) {
         /* `key' is at index -2 and `value' at index -1 */
         printf("%s - %s\n",
           lua_typename(L, lua_type(L, -2)), lua_typename(L, lua_type(L, -1)));
         lua_pop(L, 1);  /* removes `value'; keeps `key' for next iteration */
       }
}

While traversing a table,
do not call @T{lua_tolstring} directly on a key,
unless you know that the key is actually a string.
Recall that @T{lua_tolstring} @emph{changes}
the value at the given index;
this confuses the next call to @T{lua_next}.


@subsubsection{Using Tables as Arrays}
The API has functions that help to use Lua tables as arrays,
that is,
tables indexed by numbers:
@verbatim{
       void lua_rawgeti (lua_State *L, int index, int n);
       void lua_rawseti (lua_State *L, int index, int n);
}

@IndexAPI{lua_rawgeti} pushes the value of the @M{n}-th element of the table
at stack position @T{index}.
@IndexAPI{lua_rawseti} sets the value of the @M{n}-th element of the table
at stack position @T{index} to the value at the top of the stack,
removing this value from the stack.
Notice that those accesses are @emph{raw},
that is, they do not invoke metamethods.

@subsubsection{Using Tables as Records}
The API has functions that help to use Lua tables as records,
that is, tables indexed by strings:
@verbatim{
       void lua_getfield (lua_State *L, int index, const char *k);
       void lua_setfield (lua_State *L, int index, const char *k);
}

@IndexAPI{lua_getfield} pushes the value of the field named @T{k}
of the table at stack position @T{index}.
@IndexAPI{lua_setfield} sets the value of the field named @T{k}
of the table at stack position @T{index}
to the value at the top of the stack,
removing this value from the stack.


@label{globals: @subsection{Manipulating Environments}}

All global variables are kept in ordinary Lua tables,
called environments.
The initial environment is called the global environment.
This table is always at pseudo-index @IndexAPI{LUA_GLOBALSINDEX}.
The environment of the running C function is always
at pseudo-index @IndexAPI{LUA_ENVIRONINDEX}.

To access and change the value of global variables,
you can use regular table operations over an environment table.
For instance, to access the value of a global variable, do
@verbatim{
       lua_getfield(L, LUA_GLOBALSINDEX, varname);
}

The following functions get and set the environment of functions,
threads, and userdata:
@verbatim{
       void lua_getfenv (lua_State *L, int index);
       int  lua_setfenv (lua_State *L, int index);
}
@IndexAPI{lua_getfenv} pushes on the stack the environment table of
the object at index @T{index} in the stack.
@T{lua_setfenv} pops a table from the stack and sets it as
the new environment for the object at index @T{index} in the stack.
If the object at the given index is neither a function nor a thread nor
a userdata,
@T{lua_setfenv} returns 0.


@subsection{Calling Functions}

Functions defined in Lua
and @Nb{C functions} registered in Lua
can be called from the host program.
This is done using the following protocol:
First, the function to be called is pushed onto the stack;
then, the arguments to the function are pushed
in @emph{direct order}, that is, the first argument is pushed first.
Finally, the function is called using
@verbatim{
       void lua_call (lua_State *L, int nargs, int nresults);
}
@DefAPI{lua_call}
@T{nargs} is the number of arguments that you pushed onto the stack.
All arguments and the function value are popped from the stack,
and the function results are pushed.
The number of results are adjusted to @T{nresults},
unless @T{nresults} is @IndexAPI{LUA_MULTRET}.
In that case, @emph{all} results from the function are pushed.
Lua takes care that the returned values fit into the stack space.
The function results are pushed onto the stack in direct order
(the first result is pushed first),
so that after the call the last result is on the top.

The following example shows how the host program may do the
equivalent to this Lua code:
@verbatim{
       a = f("how", t.x, 14)
}
Here it is @Nb{in C}:
@verbatim{
    lua_getfield(L, LUA_GLOBALSINDEX, "t");     /* global `t' (for later use) */
    lua_getfield(L, LUA_GLOBALSINDEX, "f");          /* function to be called */
    lua_pushstring(L, "how");                                 /* 1st argument */
    lua_getfield(L, -3, "x");                 /* push result of t.x (2nd arg) */
    lua_pushinteger(L, 14);                                   /* 3rd argument */
    lua_call(L, 3, 1);         /* call function with 3 arguments and 1 result */
    lua_setfield(L, LUA_GLOBALSINDEX, "a");        /* set global variable `a' */
    lua_pop(L, 1);                               /* remove `t' from the stack */
}
Note that the code above is @Q{balanced}:
at its end, the stack is back to its original configuration.
This is considered good programming practice.


@label{lua_pcall: @subsection{Protected Calls}}

When you call a function with @T{lua_call},
any error inside the called function is propagated upwards
(with a @T{longjmp}).
If you need to handle errors,
then you should use @IndexAPI{lua_pcall}:
@verbatim{
       int lua_pcall (lua_State *L, int nargs, int nresults, int errfunc);
}
Both @T{nargs} and @T{nresults} have the same meaning as
in @T{lua_call}.
If there are no errors during the call,
@T{lua_pcall} behaves exactly like @T{lua_call}.
However, if there is any error,
@T{lua_pcall} catches it,
pushes a single value at the stack (the error message),
and returns an error code.
Like @T{lua_call},
@T{lua_pcall} always removes the function
and its arguments from the stack.

If @T{errfunc} is 0,
then the error message returned is exactly the original error message.
Otherwise, @T{errfunc} is the stack index of an
@emph{error handler function}.
(In the current implementation, that index cannot be a pseudo-index.)
In case of runtime errors,
that function will be called with the error message
and its return value will be the message returned by @T{lua_pcall}.

Typically, the error handler function is used to add more debug
information to the error message, such as a stack traceback.
Such information cannot be gathered after the return of @T{lua_pcall},
since by then the stack has unwound.

The @T{lua_pcall} function returns 0 in case of success
or one of the following error codes
(defined in @T{lua.h}):
@itemize{
@item @IndexAPI{LUA_ERRRUN} @Em a runtime error.
@item @IndexAPI{LUA_ERRMEM} @Em memory allocation error.
For such errors, Lua does not call the error handler function.
@item @IndexAPI{LUA_ERRERR} @Em{}
error while running the error handler function.
}


@label{LuacallC: @subsection{Defining C Functions}}

Lua can be extended with functions written @Nb{in C}.
These functions must be of type @IndexAPI{lua_CFunction},
which is defined as
@verbatim{
       typedef int (*lua_CFunction) (lua_State *L);
}
A @Nb{C function} receives a Lua state and returns an integer,
the number of values it wants to return to Lua.

In order to communicate properly with Lua,
a @Nb{C function} must follow the following protocol,
which defines the way parameters and results are passed:
A @Nb{C function} receives its arguments from Lua in its stack
in direct order (the first argument is pushed first).
So, when the function starts,
its first argument (if any) is at index 1.
To return values to Lua, a @Nb{C function} just pushes them onto the stack,
in direct order (the first result is pushed first),
and returns the number of results.
Any other value in the stack below the results will be properly
discharged by Lua.
Like a Lua function, a @Nb{C function} called by Lua can also return
many results.

As an example, the following function receives a variable number
of numerical arguments and returns their average and sum:
@verbatim{
       static int foo (lua_State *L) {
         int n = lua_gettop(L);    /* number of arguments */
         lua_Number sum = 0;
         int i;
         for (i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
           if (!lua_isnumber(L, i)) {
             lua_pushstring(L, "incorrect argument to function `average'");
             lua_error(L);
           }
           sum += lua_tonumber(L, i);
         }
         lua_pushnumber(L, sum/n);        /* first result */
         lua_pushnumber(L, sum);         /* second result */
         return 2;                   /* number of results */
       }
}

To create a new @Nb{C function} in Lua,
you can use @IndexAPI{lua_pushcfunction}:
@verbatim{
       void lua_pushcfunction (lua_State *L, lua_CFunction fn);
}
It receives a pointer to the function and pushes on the
stack a value of type function.
(@T{lua_pushcfunction} is actually a macro;
see next section.)

There is also the following convenience macro:
@verbatim{
       #define lua_register(L,n,f) \
               (lua_pushstring(L, n), \
                lua_pushcfunction(L, f), \
                lua_settable(L, LUA_GLOBALSINDEX))
     /* lua_State *L;    */
     /* const char *n;   */
     /* lua_CFunction f; */
}
@DefAPI{lua_register}
which receives the name the function will have in Lua
and a pointer to the function.
Thus,
the @Nb{C function} @T{foo} above may be registered in Lua as
@T{average} by calling
@verbatim{
       lua_register(L, "average", foo);
}

@label{c-closure: @subsection{Defining C Closures}}

When a @Nb{C function} is created,
it is possible to associate some values with it,
thus creating a @IndexEmph{@Nb{C closure}};
these values are then accessible to the function whenever it is called.
To associate values with a @Nb{C function},
first these values should be pushed onto the stack
(when there are multiple values, the first value is pushed first).
Then the function
@verbatim{
       void lua_pushcclosure (lua_State *L, lua_CFunction fn, int n);
}
@DefAPI{lua_pushcclosure}
is used to create and push the @Nb{C function} onto the stack,
with the argument @T{n} telling how many values should be
associated with the function
(@T{lua_pushcclosure} also pops these values from the stack);
in fact, the macro @T{lua_pushcfunction} is defined as
@T{lua_pushcclosure} with @T{n} set to 0.

Then, whenever the @Nb{C function} is called,
those values are located at specific pseudo-indices.
Those pseudo-indices are produced by a macro @IndexAPI{lua_upvalueindex}.
The first value associated with a function is at position
@T{lua_upvalueindex(1)}, and so on.
Any access to @T{lua_upvalueindex(@M{n})},
where @M{n} is greater than the number of upvalues of the
current function,
produces an acceptable (but invalid) index.

For examples of @Nb{C functions} and closures,
see the standard libraries in the official Lua distribution
(@T{src/lib/*.c}).


@label{registry: @subsection{Registry}}

Lua provides a registry,
a pre-defined table that can be used by any @Nb{C code} to
store whatever Lua value it needs to store,
specially if the @Nb{C code} needs to keep that Lua value
outside the life span of a @Nb{C function}.
This table is always located at pseudo-index
@IndexAPI{LUA_REGISTRYINDEX}.
Any @Nb{C library} can store data into this table,
as long as it chooses keys different from other libraries.
Typically, you should use as key a string containing your library name
or a light userdata with the address of a C object in your code.

The integer keys in the registry are used by the reference mechanism,
implemented by the auxiliary library,
and therefore should not be used by other purposes.


@subsection{Error Handling in C}

Internally, Lua uses the C @T{longjmp} facility to handle errors.
When Lua faces any error
(such as memory allocation errors, type errors, syntax errors)
it @emph{raises} an error, that is, it does a long jump.
A @emph{protected environment} uses @T{setjmp}
to set a recover point;
any error jumps to the most recent active recover point.

If an error happens outside any protected environment,
Lua calls a @IndexEmph{panic function}
and then calls @T{exit(EXIT_FAILURE)}.
You can replace the panic function with
@verbatim{
       lua_CFunction lua_atpanic (lua_State *L, lua_CFunction panicf);
}
Your new panic function may avoid the application exit by
never returning (e.g., doing a long jump).
The panic function can access the error message at the top of the stack.

Almost any function in the API may raise an error,
for instance due to a memory allocation error.
The following functions run in protected mode
(that is, they create a protected environment to run),
so they never raise an error:
@T{lua_open}, @T{lua_close}, @T{lua_load},
and @T{lua_pcall}.

There is yet another function that runs a given C function in protected mode:
@verbatim{
       int lua_cpcall (lua_State *L, lua_CFunction func, void *ud);
}
@DefAPI{lua_cpcall}
@T{lua_cpcall} calls @T{func} in protected mode.
@T{func} starts with only one element in its stack,
a light userdata containing @T{ud}.
In case of errors,
@T{lua_cpcall} returns the same error codes as @T{lua_pcall}
@see{lua_pcall},
plus the error object on the top of the stack;
otherwise, it returns zero, and does not change the stack.
Any value returned by @T{func} is discarded.

C code can generate a Lua error calling the function
@verbatim{
       int lua_error (lua_State *L);
}
@DefAPI{lua_error}
The error message (which actually can be any type of object)
must be on the stack top.
This function does a long jump,
and therefore never returns.


@subsection{Threads}

Lua offers partial support for multiple threads of execution.
If you have a @Nb{C library} that offers multi-threading, 
then Lua can cooperate with it to implement the equivalent facility in Lua.
Also, Lua implements its own coroutine system on top of threads.
The following function creates a new thread in Lua:
@verbatim{
       lua_State *lua_newthread (lua_State *L);
}
@DefAPI{lua_newthread}
This function pushes the thread on the stack and returns a pointer to
a @T{lua_State} that represents this new thread.
The new state returned by this function shares with the original state
all global objects (such as tables),
but has an independent run-time stack.

Each thread has an independent global environment table.
When you create a thread, this table is the same as that of the given state,
but you can replace each one independently.

There is no explicit function to close or to destroy a thread.
Threads are subject to garbage collection,
like any Lua object.

To manipulate threads as coroutines,
Lua offers the following functions:
@verbatim{
       int lua_resume (lua_State *L, int narg);
       int lua_yield  (lua_State *L, int nresults);
}
@DefAPI{lua_resume}@DefAPI{lua_yield}
To start a coroutine, you first create a new thread;
then you push on its stack the body function plus any eventual arguments;
then you call @T{lua_resume},
with @T{narg} being the number of arguments.
This call returns when the coroutine suspends or finishes its execution.
When it returns, the stack contains all values passed to @T{lua_yield},
or all values returned by the body function.
@T{lua_resume} returns 0 if there are no errors running the coroutine,
or an error code @see{lua_pcall}.
In case of errors,
the stack is not unwound,
so you can use the debug API over it;
The error message is on the top of the stack.
To restart a coroutine, you put on its stack only the values to
be passed as results from @T{yield},
and then call @T{lua_resume}.

The @T{lua_yield} function can only be called as the
return expression of a C function, as follows:
@verbatim{
       return lua_yield (L, nresults);
}
When a C function calls @T{lua_yield} in that way,
the running coroutine suspends its execution,
and the call to @T{lua_resume} that started this coroutine returns.
The parameter @T{nresults} is the number of values from the stack
that are passed as results to @T{lua_resume}.

To exchange values between different threads,
you may use @IndexAPI{lua_xmove}:
@verbatim{
       void lua_xmove (lua_State *from, lua_State *to, int n);
}
It pops @T{n} values from the stack @T{from},
and pushes them into the stack @T{to}.


@C{-------------------------------------------------------------------------}
@label{debugI: @section{The Debug Interface}}

Lua has no built-in debugging facilities.
Instead, it offers a special interface
by means of functions and @emph{hooks}.
This interface allows the construction of different
kinds of debuggers, profilers, and other tools
that need @Q{inside information} from the interpreter.

@subsection{Stack and Function Information}

The main function to get information about the interpreter runtime stack is
@verbatim{
       int lua_getstack (lua_State *L, int level, lua_Debug *ar);
}
@DefAPI{lua_getstack}
This function fills parts of a @T{lua_Debug} structure with
an identification of the @emph{activation record}
of the function executing at a given level.
@Nb{Level 0} is the current running function,
whereas level @Math{n+1} is the function that has called level @Math{n}.
When there are no errors, @T{lua_getstack} returns 1;
when called with a level greater than the stack depth,
it returns 0.

The structure @T{lua_Debug} is used to carry different pieces of
information about an active function:
@verbatim{
      typedef struct lua_Debug {
        int event;
        const char *name;      /* (n) */
        const char *namewhat;  /* (n) */
        const char *what;      /* (S) */
        const char *source;    /* (S) */
        int currentline;       /* (l) */
        int nups;              /* (u) number of upvalues */
        int linedefined;       /* (S) */
        int lastlinedefined;   /* (S) */
        char short_src[LUA_IDSIZE]; /* (S) */

        /* private part */
        ...
      } lua_Debug;
}
@DefAPI{lua_Debug}
@T{lua_getstack} fills only the private part
of this structure, for later use.
To fill the other fields of @T{lua_Debug} with useful information,
call
@verbatim{
       int lua_getinfo (lua_State *L, const char *what, lua_Debug *ar);
}
@DefAPI{lua_getinfo}
This function returns 0 on error
(for instance, an invalid option in @T{what}).
Each character in the string @T{what}
selects some fields of the structure @T{ar} to be filled,
as indicated by the letter in parentheses in the definition of @T{lua_Debug}
above:
@Char{S} fills in the fields @T{source}, @T{linedefined},
@T{lastlinedefined},
and @T{what};
@Char{l} fills in the field @T{currentline}, etc.
Moreover, @Char{f} pushes onto the stack the function that is
running at the given level.

To get information about a function that is not active
(that is, not in the stack),
you push it onto the stack
and start the @T{what} string with the character @Char{>}.
For instance, to know in which line a function @T{f} was defined,
you can write the following code:
@verbatim{
       lua_Debug ar;
       lua_getfield(L, LUA_GLOBALSINDEX, "f");  /* get global `f' */
       lua_getinfo(L, ">S", &ar);
       printf("%d\n", ar.linedefined);
}
The fields of @T{lua_Debug} have the following meaning:
@description{

@item{@Tp{source}}
If the function was defined in a string,
then @T{source} is that string.
If the function was defined in a file,
then @T{source} starts with a @Char{@At} followed by the file name.

@item{@Tp{short_src}}
A @Q{printable} version of @T{source}, to be used in error messages.

@item{@Tp{linedefined}}
the line number where the definition of the function starts.

@item{@Tp{lastlinedefined}}
the line number where the definition of the function ends.

@item{@Tp{what}} the string @T{"Lua"} if this is a Lua function,
@T{"C"} if this is a @Nb{C function},
@T{"main"} if this is the main part of a chunk,
and @T{"tail"} if this was a function that did a tail call.
In the latter case,
Lua has no other information about this function.

@item{@Tp{currentline}}
the current line where the given function is executing.
When no line information is available,
@T{currentline} is set to @Math{-1}.

@item{@Tp{name}}
a reasonable name for the given function.
Because functions in Lua are first class values,
they do not have a fixed name:
Some functions may be the value of multiple global variables,
while others may be stored only in a table field.
The @T{lua_getinfo} function checks how the function was
called to find a suitable name.
If it cannot find a name,
then @T{name} is set to @T{NULL}.

@item{@Tp{namewhat}}
Explains the @T{name} field.
The value of @T{namewhat} can be
@T{"global"}, @T{"local"}, @T{"method"},
@T{"field"}, @T{"upvalue"}, or @T{""} (the empty string),
according to how the function was called.
(Lua uses the empty string when no other option seems to apply.)

@item{@Tp{nups}}
The number of upvalues of the function.

}


@subsection{Manipulating Local Variables and Upvalues}

For the manipulation of local variables and upvalues,
the debug interface uses indices:
The first parameter or local variable has @Nb{index 1}, and so on,
until the last active local variable.
Upvalues have no particular order,
as they are active through the whole function.

The following functions allow the manipulation of the
local variables of a given activation record:
@verbatim{
       const char *lua_getlocal (lua_State *L, const lua_Debug *ar, int n);
       const char *lua_setlocal (lua_State *L, const lua_Debug *ar, int n);
}
@DefAPI{lua_getlocal}@DefAPI{lua_setlocal}
The parameter @T{ar} must be a valid activation record that was
filled by a previous call to @T{lua_getstack} or
given as argument to a hook @see{sub-hooks}.
@T{lua_getlocal} gets the index @T{n} of a local variable,
pushes the variable's value onto the stack,
and returns its name.
@T{lua_setlocal} assigns the value at the top of the stack
to the variable and returns its name.
Both functions return @T{NULL}
when the index is greater than
the number of active local variables.

The following functions allow the manipulation of the
upvalues of a given function
(unlike local variables,
the upvalues of a function are accessible even when the
function is not active):
@verbatim{
       const char *lua_getupvalue (lua_State *L, int funcindex, int n);
       const char *lua_setupvalue (lua_State *L, int funcindex, int n);
}
@DefAPI{lua_getupvalue}@DefAPI{lua_setupvalue}
These functions operate both on Lua functions and on @Nb{C functions}.
(For Lua functions,
upvalues are the external local variables that the function uses,
and that consequently are included in its closure.)
@T{funcindex} points to a function in the stack.
@T{lua_getupvalue} gets the index @T{n} of an upvalue,
pushes the upvalue's value onto the stack,
and returns its name.
@T{lua_setupvalue} assigns the value at the top of the stack
to the upvalue and returns its name.
Both functions return @T{NULL}
when the index is greater than the number of upvalues.
For @Nb{C functions}, these functions use the empty string @T{""}
as a name for all upvalues.

As an example, the following function lists the names of all
local variables and upvalues for a function at a given level of the stack:
@verbatim{
       int listvars (lua_State *L, int level) {
         lua_Debug ar;
         int i;
         const char *name;
         if (lua_getstack(L, level, &ar) == 0)
           return 0;  /* failure: no such level in the stack */
         i = 1;
         while ((name = lua_getlocal(L, &ar, i++)) != NULL) {
           printf("local %d %s\n", i-1, name);
           lua_pop(L, 1);  /* remove variable value */
         }
         lua_getinfo(L, "f", &ar);  /* retrieves function */
         i = 1;
         while ((name = lua_getupvalue(L, -1, i++)) != NULL) {
           printf("upvalue %d %s\n", i-1, name);
           lua_pop(L, 1);  /* remove upvalue value */
         }
         return 1;
       }
}


@label{sub-hooks: @subsection{Hooks}}

Lua offers a mechanism of hooks, which are
user-defined C functions that are called during the program execution.
A hook may be called in four different events:
a @emph{call} event, when Lua calls a function;
a @emph{return} event, when Lua returns from a function;
a @emph{line} event, when Lua starts executing a new line of code;
and a @emph{count} event, which happens every @Q{count} instructions.
Lua identifies these events with the following constants:
@IndexAPI{LUA_HOOKCALL},
@IndexAPI{LUA_HOOKRET} (or @IndexAPI{LUA_HOOKTAILRET}, see below),
@IndexAPI{LUA_HOOKLINE},
and @IndexAPI{LUA_HOOKCOUNT}.

A hook has type @T{lua_Hook}, defined as follows:
@verbatim{
       typedef void (*lua_Hook) (lua_State *L, lua_Debug *ar);
}
@DefAPI{lua_Hook}
You can set the hook with the following function:
@verbatim{
       int lua_sethook (lua_State *L, lua_Hook func, int mask, int count);
}
@DefAPI{lua_sethook}
@T{func} is the hook.
@T{mask} specifies on which events the hook will be called:
It is formed by a disjunction of the constants
@IndexAPI{LUA_MASKCALL},
@IndexAPI{LUA_MASKRET},
@IndexAPI{LUA_MASKLINE},
and @IndexAPI{LUA_MASKCOUNT}.
The @T{count} argument is only meaningful when the mask
includes @T{LUA_MASKCOUNT}.
For each event, the hook is called as explained below:
@description{
@item{The call hook} is called when the interpreter calls a function.
The hook is called just after Lua enters the new function.
@item{The return hook} is called when the interpreter returns from a function.
The hook is called just before Lua leaves the function.
@item{The line hook} is called when the interpreter is about to
start the execution of a new line of code,
or when it jumps back in the code (even to the same line).
(This event only happens while Lua is executing a Lua function.)
@item{The count hook} is called after the interpreter executes every
@T{count} instructions.
(This event only happens while Lua is executing a Lua function.)
}

A hook is disabled by setting @T{mask} to zero.

You can get the current hook, the current mask,
and the current count with the following functions:
@verbatim{
       lua_Hook lua_gethook      (lua_State *L);
       int      lua_gethookmask  (lua_State *L);
       int      lua_gethookcount (lua_State *L);
}
@DefAPI{lua_gethook}@DefAPI{lua_gethookmask}@DefAPI{lua_gethookcount}

Whenever a hook is called, its @T{ar} argument has its field
@T{event} set to the specific event that triggered the hook.
Moreover, for line events, the field @T{currentline} is also set.
To get the value of any other field in @T{ar},
the hook must call @T{lua_getinfo}.
For return events, @T{event} may be @T{LUA_HOOKRET},
the normal value, or @T{LUA_HOOKTAILRET}.
In the latter case, Lua is simulating a return from
a function that did a tail call;
in this case, it is useless to call @T{lua_getinfo}.

While Lua is running a hook, it disables other calls to hooks.
Therefore, if a hook calls back Lua to execute a function or a chunk,
that execution occurs without any calls to hooks.


@C{-------------------------------------------------------------------------}
@label{libraries: @section{Standard Libraries}}

The standard libraries provide useful functions
that are implemented directly through the C API.
Some of these functions provide essential services to the language
(e.g., @T{type} and @T{getmetatable});
others provide access to @Q{outside} services (e.g., I/O);
and others could be implemented in Lua itself,
but are quite useful or have critical performance to
deserve an implementation in C (e.g., @T{sort}).

All libraries are implemented through the official C API
and are provided as separate @Nb{C modules}.
Currently, Lua has the following standard libraries:
@itemize{
@item basic library;
@item string manipulation;
@item table manipulation;
@item mathematical functions (sin, log, etc.);
@item input and output;
@item operating system facilities;
@item debug facilities.
}
Except for the basic library,
each library provides all its functions as fields of a global table
or as methods of its objects.

To have access to these libraries,
the @Nb{C host} program must first call the functions
@T{luaopen_base} (for the basic library),
@T{luaopen_string} (for the string library),
@T{luaopen_table} (for the table library),
@T{luaopen_math} (for the mathematical library),
@T{luaopen_io} (for the I/O and the Operating System libraries),
and @T{luaopen_debug} (for the debug library).
These functions are declared in @T{lualib.h}.
@DefAPI{luaopen_base}
@DefAPI{luaopen_string}
@DefAPI{luaopen_table}
@DefAPI{luaopen_math}
@DefAPI{luaopen_io}
@DefAPI{luaopen_debug}


@label{predefined: @subsection{Basic Functions}}

The basic library provides some core functions to Lua.
If you do not include this library in your application,
you should check carefully whether you need to provide some alternative
implementation for some of its facilities.


@LibEntry{assert (v [, message])}
Issues an  error when
the value of its argument @T{v} is @nil or @False;
otherwise, returns all its arguments.
@T{message} is an error message;
when absent, it defaults to @Q{assertion failed!}

@LibEntry{collectgarbage (opt [, arg])}

This function is a generic interface to the garbage collector.
It performs different functions according to its first agument, @T{opt}:
@description{
@item{@Q{stop}} stops the garbage collector.
@item{@Q{restart}} restarts the garbage collector.
@item{@Q{collect}} performs a full garbage-collection cycle.
@item{@Q{count}} returns the total memory in use by Lua (in Kbytes).
@item{@Q{step}} performs a few garbage-collection steps.
The number of steps is controlled by @T{arg}
(larger values mean more steps) in a non-specified way.
The size of each step is also not specified;
if you want to control the step size
you must tune experimentally the value of @T{arg}.
@item{@Q{steppause}}
sets @M{@Tp{arg}/100} as the new value for the @emph{pause} of
the collector @see{GC}.
@item{@Q{setstepmul}}
sets @M{@Tp{arg}/100} as the new value for the @emph{step multiplier} of
the collector @see{GC}.
}

@LibEntry{dofile (filename)}
Opens the named file and executes its contents as a Lua chunk.
When called without arguments,
@T{dofile} executes the contents of the standard input (@T{stdin}).
Returns any value returned by the chunk.
In case of errors, @T{dofile} propagates the error
to its caller (that is, it does not run in protected mode).

@label{pdf-error: @LibEntry{error (message [, level])}}
Terminates the last protected function called
and returns @T{message} as the error message.
Function @T{error} never returns.

Usually, @T{error} adds some information about the error position
at the beginning of the message.
The @T{level} argument specifies how to get the error position.
With level 1 (the default), the error position is where the
@T{error} function was called.
Level 2 points the error to where the function
that called @T{error} was called; and so on.
Passing a level 0 avoids the addition of error position information
to the message.

@LibEntry{_G}
A global variable (not a function) that
holds the global environment (that is, @T{_G._G = _G}).
Lua itself does not use this variable;
changing its value does not affect any environment.
(Use @T{setfenv} to change environments.)

@label{pdf-getfenv: @LibEntry{getfenv (f)}}
Returns the current environment in use by the function.
@T{f} can be a Lua function or a number,
which specifies the function at that stack level:
Level 1 is the function calling @T{getfenv}.
If the given function is not a Lua function,
or if @T{f} is 0,
@T{getfenv} returns the global environment.
The default for @T{f} is 1.

@label{pdf-getmetatable: @LibEntry{getmetatable (object)}}

If @T{object} does not have a metatable, returns @nil.
Otherwise,
if the object's metatable has a @T{"__metatable"} field,
returns the associated value.
Otherwise, returns the metatable of the given object.

@LibEntry{ipairs (t)}

Returns an iterator function, the table @T{t}, and 0,
so that the construction
@verbatim{
       for i,v in ipairs(t) do ... end
}
will iterate over the pairs (@T{1,t[1]}), (@T{2,t[2]}), @ldots,
up to the first integer key with a nil value in the table.

@label{pdf-load: @LibEntry{load (func [, chunkname])}}

Loads a chunk using function @T{func} to get its pieces.
Each call to @T{func} must return a string that concatentates
with previous results.
A return of @nil (or no value) signals the end of the chunk.

If there are no errors, 
returns the compiled chunk as a function;
otherwise, returns @nil plus the error message.
The environment of the returned function is the global environment.

@T{chunkname} is used as the chunk name for error messages
and debug information.

@LibEntry{loadfile (filename)}

Similar to @T{load} @see{pdf-load},
but gets the chunk from file @T{filename}.

@LibEntry{loadlib (libname, funcname)}

Links the program with the dynamic C library @T{libname}.
Inside this library, looks for a function @T{funcname}
and returns this function as a C function.

@T{libname} must be the complete file name of the C library,
including any eventual path and extension.

This function is not supported by ANSI C.
As such, it is only available on some platforms
(Windows, Linux, Solaris, BSD, plus other Unix systems that
support the @T{dlfcn} standard).

@LibEntry{loadstring (string [, chunkname])}

Similar to @T{load} @see{pdf-load},
but gets the chunk from the given string.

To load and run a given string, use the idiom
@verbatim{
      assert(loadstring(s))()
}

@LibEntry{module (name)}

Creates a module.
If there is a global table with the given name,
that is the module (a table which we call here @T{t}).
Otherwise creates a new table @T{t} and
sets it as the value of the global @T{name}.
This function also initializes @T{t._NAME} with the given name,
@T{t._M} with the module (@T{t} itself),
and @T{t._PACKAGE} with the package name
(the full module name minus last component; see below??).
Moreover, it sets a metatable for @T{t} with
its @T{__index} field refering to the global environment,
so that this module inherits undefined values from the global environment.

Finally, @T{module} sets @T{t} as the new environment
of the current function and the new value of @T{package.loaded[name]},
so that @T{require} returns @T{t} @see{pdf-require}.

If @T{name} is a compound name
(that is, one with components separated by dots)
@T{module} creates (or reuses, if they already exists)
tables for each component.
For instance, if @T{name} is @T{a.b.c},
@T{module} stores the module table in field @T{c} of
field @T{b} of global @T{a}.

@LibEntry{next (table [, index])}
Allows a program to traverse all fields of a table.
Its first argument is a table and its second argument
is an index in this table.
@T{next} returns the next index of the table and the
value associated with the index.
When called with @nil as its second argument,
@T{next} returns the first index
of the table and its associated value.
When called with the last index,
or with @nil in an empty table,
@T{next} returns @nil.
If the second argument is absent, then it is interpreted as @nil.

Lua has no declaration of fields;
There is no difference between a
field not present in a table or a field with value @nil.
Therefore, @T{next} only considers fields with non-@nil values.
The order in which the indices are enumerated is not specified,
@emph{even for numeric indices}.
(To traverse a table in numeric order,
use a numerical @rwd{for} or the @T{ipairs} function.)

The behavior of @T{next} is @emph{undefined} if,
during the traversal,
you assign any value to a non-existent field in the table.

@LibEntry{pairs (t)}

Returns the @T{next} function and the table @T{t} (plus a @nil),
so that the construction
@verbatim{
       for k,v in pairs(t) do ... end
}
will iterate over all key@En{}value pairs of table @T{t}.

@label{pdf-pcall: @LibEntry{pcall (f, arg1, arg2, @ldots)}}

Calls function @T{f} with
the given arguments in protected mode.
That means that any error @Nb{inside @T{f}} is not propagated;
instead, @T{pcall} catches the error
and returns a status code.
Its first result is the status code (a boolean),
which is true if the call succeeds without errors.
In such case, @T{pcall} also returns all results from the call,
after this first result.
In case of any error, @T{pcall} returns @False plus the error message.

@LibEntry{print (e1, e2, @ldots)}
Receives any number of arguments,
and prints their values in @T{stdout},
using the @T{tostring} function to convert them to strings.
This function is not intended for formatted output,
but only as a quick way to show a value,
typically for debugging.
For formatted output, use @T{format} @see{format}.

@LibEntry{rawequal (v1, v2)}
Checks whether @T{v1} is equal to @T{v2},
without invoking any metamethod.
Returns a boolean.

@LibEntry{rawget (table, index)}
Gets the real value of @T{table[index]},
without invoking any metamethod.
@T{table} must be a table;
@T{index} is any value different from @nil.

@LibEntry{rawset (table, index, value)}
Sets the real value of @T{table[index]} to @T{value},
without invoking any metamethod.
@T{table} must be a table,
@T{index} is any value different from @nil,
and @T{value} is any Lua value.

@label{pdf-require: @LibEntry{require (modname)}}

Loads the given module.
The function starts by looking into the table @IndexVerb{package.loaded}
to determine whether @T{modname} is already loaded.
If it is, then @T{require} returns the value stored
at @T{package.loaded[modname]}.
Otherwise, it tries to find a loader for that module.

To find a loader,
first @T{require} queries @T{package.preload[modname]}.
If it is a true value,
that value (which should be a function) is the loader.
Otherwise @T{require} searches for a Lua loader using the
path stored in @IndexVerb{package.path}.
if that also fails, it searches for a C loader using the
path stored in @IndexVerb{package.cpath}.

A path is a sequence of @emph{templates} separated by semicolons.
For each template, @T{require} will change each interrogation
mark in the template by @T{filename},
which is @T{modname} with each dot replaced by a
@Q{directory separator} (such as @St{/} in Unix);
then it will try to load the resulting file name.
So, for instance, if the Lua path is
@verbatim{
  "./?.lua;./?.lc;/usr/local/?/?.lua;/lasttry"
}
the search for a Lua loader will try to load the files
@T{./mod.lua},
@T{./mod.lc},
@T{/usr/local/mod/mod.lua},
and @T{/lasttry}, in that order.

At start-up, Lua initializes @IndexVerb{package.path} with
the value of the environment variable @IndexVerb{LUA_PATH} or
with a compiled-defined default path,
if the environment variable is not defined.
Any @St{;;} in @IndexVerb{LUA_PATH} is replaced by the default path.
Lua initializes the C path @IndexVerb{package.cpath} in the same way,
using the environment variable @IndexVerb{LUA_CPATH}
(plus another compiled-defined default path).

Once a loader is found,
@T{require} sets @IndexVerb{package.loaded[modname]} to true and
calls the loader with a sinle argument, @T{modname}.
If the loader returns any value,
@T{require} assigns it to @IndexVerb{package.loaded[modname]}.
In any case, require returns the
final value of @IndexVerb{package.loaded[modname]}.

If there is any error loading or running the module,
or if it cannot find any loader for that module,
then @T{require} signals an error. 


>>>> .common?

@LibEntry{select (index, ...)}

If @T{index} is a number,
returns all argument after argument number @T{index}.
Otherwise, @T{index} must be the string @T{"#"},
and @T{select} returns the total number of extra arguments it received.

@label{setfenv: @LibEntry{setfenv (f, table)}}

Sets the environment to be used by the given function.
@T{f} can be a Lua function or a number,
which specifies the function at that stack level:
Level 1 is the function calling @T{setfenv}.
@T{setfenv} returns the given function.

As a special case, when @T{f} is 0 @T{setfenv} changes
the environment of the running thread.
In this case, @T{setfenv} returns no values.

@LibEntry{setmetatable (table, metatable)}

Sets the metatable for the given table.
(You cannot change the metatable of other types from Lua.)
If @T{metatable} is @nil,
removes the metatable of the given table.
If the original metatable has a @T{"__metatable"} field,
raises an error.

This function returns @T{table}.

@LibEntry{tonumber (e [, base])}
Tries to convert its argument to a number.
If the argument is already a number or a string convertible
to a number, then @T{tonumber} returns that number;
otherwise, it returns @nil.

An optional argument specifies the base to interpret the numeral.
The base may be any integer between 2 and 36, inclusive.
In bases @Nb{above 10}, the letter @Char{A} (in either upper or lower case)
@Nb{represents 10}, @Char{B} @Nb{represents 11}, and so forth,
with @Char{Z} representing 35.
In base 10 (the default), the number may have a decimal part,
as well as an optional exponent part @see{coercion}.
In other bases, only unsigned integers are accepted.

@LibEntry{tostring (e)}
Receives an argument of any type and
converts it to a string in a reasonable format.
For complete control of how numbers are converted,
use @T{string.format} @see{format}.

If the metatable of @T{e} has a @T{"__tostring"} field,
@T{tostring} calls the corresponding value
with @T{e} as argument,
and uses the result of the call as its result.

@label{pdf-type: @LibEntry{type (v)}}
Returns the type of its only argument, coded as a string.
The possible results of this function are
@T{"nil"} (a string, not the value @nil),
@T{"number"},
@T{"string"},
@T{"boolean},
@T{"table"},
@T{"function"},
@T{"thread"},
and @T{"userdata"}.

@LibEntry{unpack (list [, i [, j]])}
Returns the elements from the given list.
This function is equivalent to
@verbatim{
  return list[i], list[i+1], ..., list[j]
}
except that the above code can be written only for a fixed number
of elements.
By default, @T{i} is 1 and @T{j} is the length of the list,
as defined by the length operator.

@LibEntry{_VERSION}
A global variable (not a function) that
holds a string containing the current interpreter version.
The current contents of this variable is @T{"Lua @Version"}.

@LibEntry{xpcall (f, err)}

This function is similar to @T{pcall},
except that you can set a new error handler.

@T{xpcall} calls function @T{f} in protected mode,
using @T{err} as the error handler.
Any error inside @T{f} is not propagated;
instead, @T{xpcall} catches the error,
calls the @T{err} function with the original error object,
and returns a status code.
Its first result is the status code (a boolean),
which is true if the call succeeds without errors.
In such case, @T{xpcall} also returns all results from the call,
after this first result.
In case of any error,
@T{xpcall} returns false plus the result from @T{err}.



@subsection{Coroutine Manipulation}

The operations related to coroutines comprise a sub-library of
the basic library and come inside the table @DefAPI{coroutine}.
See @See{coroutine} for a general description of coroutines.

@LibEntry{coroutine.create (f)}

Creates a new coroutine, with body @T{f}.
@T{f} must be a Lua function.
Returns this new coroutine,
an object with type @T{"thread"}.

@LibEntry{coroutine.resume (co, val1, @ldots)}

Starts or continues the execution of coroutine @T{co}.
The first time you resume a coroutine,
it starts running its body.
The arguments @T{val1}, @ldots go as the arguments to the body function.
If the coroutine has yielded,
@T{resume} restarts it;
the arguments @T{val1}, @ldots go as the results from the yield.

If the coroutine runs without any errors,
@T{resume} returns @True plus any values passed to @T{yield}
(if the coroutine yields) or any values returned by the body function
(if the coroutine terminates).
If there is any error,
@T{resume} returns @False plus the error message.

@LibEntry{coroutine.running ()}

Returns the running coroutine,
or @nil when called by the main thread.

@LibEntry{coroutine.status (co)}

Returns the status of coroutine @T{co}, as a string:
@T{"running"},
if the coroutine is running (that is, it called @T{status});
@T{"suspended"}, if the coroutine is suspended in a call to @T{yield},
or if it has not started running yet;
@T{"normal"} if the coroutine is active but not running
(that is, it has resumed another coroutine);
and @T{"dead"} if the coroutine has finished its body function,
or if it has stopped with an error.

@LibEntry{coroutine.wrap (f)}

Creates a new coroutine, with body @T{f}.
@T{f} must be a Lua function.
Returns a function that resumes the coroutine each time it is called.
Any arguments passed to the function behave as the
extra arguments to @T{resume}.
Returns the same values returned by @T{resume},
except the first boolean.
In case of error, propagates the error.

@LibEntry{coroutine.yield (val1, @ldots)}

Suspends the execution of the calling coroutine.
The coroutine cannot be running neither a C function,
nor a metamethod, nor an iterator.
Any arguments to @T{yield} go as extra results to @T{resume}.



@subsection{String Manipulation}

This library provides generic functions for string manipulation,
such as finding and extracting substrings, and pattern matching.
When indexing a string in Lua, the first character is at @Nb{position 1}
(not @Nb{at 0}, as in C).
Indices are allowed to be negative and are interpreted as indexing backwards,
from the end of the string.
Thus, the last character is at position @Math{-1}, and so on.

The string library provides all its functions inside the table
@IndexLIB{string}.

@LibEntry{string.byte (s [, i [, j]])}
Returns the internal numerical codes of the characters @T{s[i]},
@T{s[i+1]}, @ldots, @T{s[j]}.
The default value for @T{i} is Nb{}1;
the default value for @T{j} is @T{i}.

Note that numerical codes are not necessarily portable across platforms.

@LibEntry{string.char (i1, i2, @ldots)}
Receives 0 or more integers.
Returns a string with length equal to the number of arguments,
in which each character has the internal numerical code equal
to its correspondent argument.

Note that numerical codes are not necessarily portable across platforms.

@LibEntry{string.dump (function)}

Returns a binary representation of the given function,
so that a later @T{loadstring} on that string returns
a copy of the function.
@T{function} must be a Lua function.

@LibEntry{string.find (s, pattern [, init [, plain]])}
Looks for the first @emph{match} of
@T{pattern} in the string @T{s}.
If it finds one, then @T{find} returns the indices @Nb{of @T{s}}
where this occurrence starts and ends;
otherwise, it returns @nil.
A third, optional numerical argument @T{init} specifies
where to start the search;
its default value @Nb{is 1} and may be negative.
A value of @True as a fourth, optional argument @T{plain}
turns off the pattern matching facilities,
so the function does a plain @Q{find substring} operation,
with no characters in @T{pattern} being considered @Q{magic}.
Note that if @T{plain} is given, then @T{init} must be given too.

@label{format: @LibEntry{string.format (formatstring, e1, e2, @ldots)}}
Returns a formatted version of its variable number of arguments
following the description given in its first argument (which must be a string).
The format string follows the same rules as the @T{printf} family of
standard @Nb{C functions}.
The only differences are that the options/modifiers
@T{*}, @T{l}, @T{L}, @T{n}, @T{p},
and @T{h} are not supported,
and there is an extra option, @T{q}.
The @T{q} option formats a string in a form suitable to be safely read
back by the Lua interpreter:
The string is written between double quotes,
and all double quotes, newlines, and backslashes in the string
are correctly escaped when written.
For instance, the call
@verbatim{
       string.format('%q', 'a string with "quotes" and \n new line')
}
will produce the string:
@verbatim{
"a string with \"quotes\" and \
 new line"
}

The options @T{c}, @T{d}, @T{E}, @T{e}, @T{f},
@T{g}, @T{G}, @T{i}, @T{o}, @T{u}, @T{X}, and @T{x} all
expect a number as argument,
whereas @T{q} and @T{s} expect a string.

This function does not accept string values
containing embedded zeros.

@LibEntry{string.gmatch (s, pat)}
Returns an iterator function that,
each time it is called,
returns the next captures from pattern @T{pat} over string @T{s}.

If @T{pat} specifies no captures,
then the whole match is produced in each call.

As an example, the following loop
@verbatim{
  s = "hello world from Lua"
  for w in string.gmatch(s, "%a+") do
    print(w)
  end
}
will iterate over all the words from string @T{s},
printing one per line.
The next example collects all pairs @T{key=value} from the
given string into a table:
@verbatim{
  t = {}
  s = "from=world, to=Lua"
  for k, v in string.gmatch(s, "(%w+)=(%w+)") do
    t[k] = v
  end
}

@LibEntry{string.gsub (s, pat, repl [, n])}
Returns a copy of @T{s}
in which all occurrences of the pattern @T{pat} have been
replaced by a replacement string specified by @T{repl}.
@T{gsub} also returns, as a second value,
the total number of substitutions made.

If @T{repl} is a string, then its value is used for replacement.
The character @T{%} works as an escape character:
Any sequence in @T{repl} of the form @T{%}@M{n},
with @M{n} between 1 and 9,
stands for the value of the @M{n}-th captured substring (see below).
The sequence @T{%%} stands for a single @T{%}.

If @T{repl} is a function, then this function is called every time a
match occurs, with all captured substrings passed as arguments,
in order;
if the pattern specifies no captures,
then the whole match is passed as a sole argument.
If the value returned by this function is a string,
then it is used as the replacement string;
otherwise, the replacement string is the empty string.

The optional last parameter @T{n} limits
the maximum number of substitutions to occur.
For instance, when @T{n} is 1 only the first occurrence of
@T{pat} is replaced.

Here are some examples:
@verbatim{
   x = string.gsub("hello world", "(%w+)", "%1 %1")
   --> x="hello hello world world"

   x = string.gsub("hello world", "(%w+)", "%1 %1", 1)
   --> x="hello hello world"

   x = string.gsub("hello world from Lua", "(%w+)%s*(%w+)", "%2 %1")
   --> x="world hello Lua from"

   x = string.gsub("home = $HOME, user = $USER", "%$(%w+)", os.getenv)
   --> x="home = /home/roberto, user = roberto"

   x = string.gsub("4+5 = $return 4+5$", "%$(.-)%$", function (s)
         return loadstring(s)()
       end)
   --> x="4+5 = 9"

   local t = {name="lua", version="5.0"}
   x = string.gsub("$name_$version.tar.gz", "%$(%w+)", function (v)
         return t[v]
       end)
   --> x="lua_5.0.tar.gz"
}

@LibEntry{string.len (s)}
Receives a string and returns its length.
The empty string @T{""} has length 0.
Embedded zeros are counted,
so @T{"a\000bc\000"} has length 5.

@LibEntry{string.lower (s)}
Receives a string and returns a copy of that string with all
uppercase letters changed to lowercase.
All other characters are left unchanged.
The definition of what is an uppercase letter depends on the current locale.

@LibEntry{string.match (s, pattern [, init])}
Looks for the first @emph{match} of
@T{pattern} in the string @T{s}.
If it finds one, then @T{match} returns
the captures from the pattern;
otherwise it returns @nil.
If @T{pattern} specifies no captures,
then the whole match is returned.
A third, optional numerical argument @T{init} specifies
where to start the search;
its default value @Nb{is 1} and may be negative.

@LibEntry{string.rep (s, n)}
Returns a string that is the concatenation of @T{n} copies of
the string @T{s}.

@LibEntry{string.reverse (s)}
Returns a string that is the string @T{s} reversed.

@LibEntry{string.sub (s, i [, j])}
Returns the substring of @T{s} that
starts at @T{i}  and continues until @T{j};
@T{i} and @T{j} may be negative.
If @T{j} is absent, then it is assumed to be equal to @Math{-1}
(which is the same as the string length).
In particular,
the call @T{string.sub(s,1,j)} returns a prefix of @T{s}
with length @T{j},
and @T{string.sub(s, -i)} returns a suffix of @T{s}
with length @T{i}.

@LibEntry{string.upper (s)}
Receives a string and returns a copy of that string with all
lowercase letters changed to uppercase.
All other characters are left unchanged.
The definition of what is a lowercase letter depends on the current locale.

@label{pm: @subsubsectionX{Patterns}}

@paragraph{Character Class:}
A @Def{character class} is used to represent a set of characters.
The following combinations are allowed in describing a character class:
@description{
@item{@emph{x}} (where @emph{x} is not one of the magic characters
@T{^$()%.[]*+-?})
@Em represents the character @emph{x} itself.
@item{@Tp{.}} @Em (a dot) represents all characters.
@item{@Tp{%a}} @Em represents all letters.
@item{@Tp{%c}} @Em represents all control characters.
@item{@Tp{%d}} @Em represents all digits.
@item{@Tp{%l}} @Em represents all lowercase letters.
@item{@Tp{%p}} @Em represents all punctuation characters.
@item{@Tp{%s}} @Em represents all space characters.
@item{@Tp{%u}} @Em represents all uppercase letters.
@item{@Tp{%w}} @Em represents all alphanumeric characters.
@item{@Tp{%x}} @Em represents all hexadecimal digits.
@item{@Tp{%z}} @Em represents the character with representation 0.
@item{@Tp{%@M{x}}} (where @M{x} is any non-alphanumeric character)  @Em{}
represents the character @M{x}.
This is the standard way to escape the magic characters.
Any punctuation character (even the non magic)
can be preceded by a @Char{%}
when used to represent itself in a pattern.

@item{@Tp{[@M{set}]}} @Em{}
represents the class which is the union of all
characters in @M{set}.
A range of characters may be specified by
separating the end characters of the range with a @Char{-}.
All classes @T{%}@emph{x} described above may also be used as
components in @M{set}.
All other characters in @M{set} represent themselves.
For example, @T{[%w_]} (or @T{[_%w]})
represents all alphanumeric characters plus the underscore,
@T{[0-7]} represents the octal digits,
and @T{[0-7%l%-]} represents the octal digits plus
the lowercase letters plus the @Char{-} character.

The interaction between ranges and classes is not defined.
Therefore, patterns like @T{[%a-z]} or @T{[a-%%]}
have no meaning.

@item{@Tp{[^@M{set}]}} @Em{}
represents the complement of @M{set},
where @M{set} is interpreted as above.
}
For all classes represented by single letters (@T{%a}, @T{%c}, etc.),
the corresponding uppercase letter represents the complement of the class.
For instance, @T{%S} represents all non-space characters.

The definitions of letter, space, and other character groups
depend on the current locale.
In particular, the class @T{[a-z]} may not be equivalent to @T{%l}.

@paragraph{Pattern Item:}
A @Def{pattern item} may be
@itemize{
@item 
a single character class,
which matches any single character in the class;
@item 
a single character class followed by @Char{*},
which matches 0 or more repetitions of characters in the class.
These repetition items will always match the longest possible sequence;
@item 
a single character class followed by @Char{+},
which matches 1 or more repetitions of characters in the class.
These repetition items will always match the longest possible sequence;
@item 
a single character class followed by @Char{-},
which also matches 0 or more repetitions of characters in the class.
Unlike @Char{*},
these repetition items will always match the @emph{shortest} possible sequence;
@item 
a single character class followed by @Char{?},
which matches 0 or 1 occurrence of a character in the class;
@item 
@T{%@M{n}}, for @M{n} between 1 and 9;
such item matches a substring equal to the @M{n}-th captured string
(see below);
@item 
@T{%b@M{xy}}, where @M{x} and @M{y} are two distinct characters;
such item matches strings that start @Nb{with @M{x}}, end @Nb{with @M{y}},
and where the @M{x} and @M{y} are @emph{balanced}.
This means that, if one reads the string from left to right,
counting @Math{+1} for an @M{x} and @Math{-1} for a @M{y},
the ending @M{y} is the first @M{y} where the count reaches 0.
For instance, the item @T{%b()} matches expressions with
balanced parentheses.
}

@paragraph{Pattern:}
A @Def{pattern} is a sequence of pattern items.
A @Char{^} at the beginning of a pattern anchors the match at the
beginning of the subject string.
A @Char{$} at the end of a pattern anchors the match at the
end of the subject string.
At other positions,
@Char{^} and @Char{$} have no special meaning and represent themselves.

@paragraph{Captures:}
A pattern may contain sub-patterns enclosed in parentheses;
they describe @Def{captures}.
When a match succeeds, the substrings of the subject string
that match captures are stored (@emph{captured}) for future use.
Captures are numbered according to their left parentheses.
For instance, in the pattern @T{"(a*(.)%w(%s*))"},
the part of the string matching @T{"a*(.)%w(%s*)"} is
stored as the first capture (and therefore has @Nb{number 1});
the character matching @T{.} is captured with @Nb{number 2},
and the part matching @T{%s*} has @Nb{number 3}.

As a special case, the empty capture @T{()} captures
the current string position (a number).
For instance, if we apply the pattern @T{"()aa()"} on the
string @T{"flaaap"}, there will be two captures: 3 and 5.

A pattern cannot contain embedded zeros.  Use @T{%z} instead.


@subsection{Table Manipulation}
This library provides generic functions for table manipulation.
It provides all its functions inside the table @IndexLIB{table}.

Most functions in the table library assume that the table
represents an array or a list.
For those functions, when we talk about @Q{the length} of a table
we mean the result of the length operator.

@LibEntry{table.concat (table [, sep [, i [, j]]])}
Returns @T{table[i]..sep..table[i+1] ... sep..table[j]}.
The default value for @T{sep} is the empty string,
the default for @T{i} is 1,
and the default for @T{j} is the length of the table.
If @T{i} is greater than @T{j}, returns the empty string.

@LibEntry{table.sort (table [, comp])}
Sorts table elements in a given order, @emph{in-place},
from @T{table[1]} to @T{table[n]},
where @T{n} is the length of the table.
If @T{comp} is given,
then it must be a function that receives two table elements,
and returns true
when the first is less than the second
(so that @T{not comp(a[i+1],a[i])} will be true after the sort).
If @T{comp} is not given,
then the standard Lua operator @T{<} is used instead.

The sort algorithm is not stable,
that is, elements considered equal by the given order
may have their relative positions changed by the sort.

@LibEntry{table.insert (table, [pos,] value)}

Inserts element @T{value} at position @T{pos} in @T{table},
shifting up other elements to open space, if necessary.
The default value for @T{pos} is @T{n+1},
where @T{n} is the length of the table @see{len-op},
so that a call @T{table.insert(t,x)} inserts @T{x} at the end
of table @T{t}.

@LibEntry{table.remove (table [, pos])}

Removes from @T{table} the element at position @T{pos},
shifting down other elements to close the space, if necessary.
Returns the value of the removed element.
The default value for @T{pos} is @T{n},
where @T{n} is the length of the table,
so that a call @T{table.remove(t)} removes the last element
of table @T{t}.


@label{mathlib: @subsection{Mathematical Functions}}

This library is an interface to the standard @Nb{C math} library.
It provides all its functions inside the table @IndexLIB{math}.
The library provides the following functions:
@DefLIB{math.abs}@DefLIB{math.acos}@DefLIB{math.asin}@DefLIB{math.atan}
@DefLIB{math.atan2}@DefLIB{math.ceil}@DefLIB{math.cos}@DefLIB{math.cosh}
@DefLIB{math.def}@DefLIB{math.exp}
@DefLIB{math.floor}@DefLIB{math.log}@DefLIB{math.log10}
@DefLIB{math.max}@DefLIB{math.min}@DefLIB{math.fmod}
@DefLIB{math.pow}@DefLIB{math.rad}@DefLIB{math.sin}
@DefLIB{math.sqrt}@DefLIB{math.tan}@DefLIB{math.modf}
@DefLIB{math.frexp}@DefLIB{math.ldexp}@DefLIB{math.random}
@DefLIB{math.randomseed}
@DefLIB{math.sinh}@DefLIB{math.tanh}
@verbatim{
       math.abs     math.acos    math.asin    math.atan    math.atan2
       math.ceil    math.cosh    math.cos     math.deg     math.exp
       math.floor   math.fmod    math.frexp   math.ldexp   math.log
       math.log10   math.max     math.min     math.modf    math.pow
       math.rad     math.random  math.randomseed           math.sin
       math.sinh    math.sqrt    math.tan     math.tanh
}
plus a variable @IndexLIB{math.pi} and
a variable @IndexLIB{math.huge},
with the value @IndexVerb{HUGE_VAL}.
Most of those functions
are only interfaces to the corresponding functions in the @Nb{C library}.
All trigonometric functions work in radians.
The functions @T{math.deg} and @T{math.rad} convert
between radians and degrees.

The function @T{math.max} returns the maximum
value of its numeric arguments.
Similarly, @T{math.min} computes the minimum.
Both can be used with 1, 2, or more arguments.

The function @T{math.modf} corresponds to the @T{modf} C function.
It returns two values:
The integral part and the fractional part of its argument.
The function @T{math.frexp} also returns 2 values:
The normalized fraction and the expoent of its argument.

The functions @T{math.random} and @T{math.randomseed}
are interfaces to the simple random generator functions
@T{rand} and @T{srand} that are provided by @Nb{ANSI C}.
(No guarantees can be given for their statistical properties.)
When called without arguments,
@T{math.random} returns a pseudo-random real number
in the range @Math{[0,1)}.  @C{]}
When called with a number @Math{n},
@T{math.random} returns a pseudo-random integer in the range @Math{[1,n]}.
When called with two arguments, @Math{l} and @Math{u},
@T{math.random} returns a pseudo-random integer in the range @Math{[l,u]}.
The @T{math.randomseed} function sets a @Q{seed}
for the pseudo-random generator:
Equal seeds produce equal sequences of numbers.


@label{libio: @subsection{Input and Output Facilities}}

The I/O library provides two different styles for file manipulation.
The first one uses implicit file descriptors,
that is, there are operations to set a default input file and a
default output file,
and all input/output operations are over those default files.
The second style uses explicit file descriptors.

When using implicit file descriptors,
all operations are supplied by table @IndexLIB{io}.
When using explicit file descriptors,
the operation @IndexLIB{io.open} returns a file descriptor
and then all operations are supplied as methods of the file descriptor.

The table @T{io} also provides
three predefined file descriptors with their usual meanings from C:
@IndexLIB{io.stdin}, @IndexLIB{io.stdout}, and @IndexLIB{io.stderr}.

Unless otherwise stated,
all I/O functions return @nil on failure
(plus an error message as a second result)
and some value different from @nil on success.

@LibEntry{io.close ([file])}

Equivalent to @T{file:close()}.
Without a @T{file}, closes the default output file.

@LibEntry{io.flush ()}

Equivalent to @T{file:flush} over the default output file.

@LibEntry{io.input ([file])}

When called with a file name, it opens the named file (in text mode),
and sets its handle as the default input file.
When called with a file handle,
it simply sets that file handle as the default input file.
When called without parameters,
it returns the current default input file.

In case of errors this function raises the error,
instead of returning an error code.

@LibEntry{io.lines ([filename])}

Opens the given file name in read mode
and returns an iterator function that,
each time it is called,
returns a new line from the file.
Therefore, the construction
@verbatim{
       for line in io.lines(filename) do ... end
}
will iterate over all lines of the file.
When the iterator function detects the end of file,
it returns @nil (to finish the loop) and automatically closes the file.

The call @T{io.lines()} (without a file name) is equivalent
to @T{io.input():lines()}, that is, it iterates over the
lines of the default input file.
In that case it does not close the file when the loop ends.

@LibEntry{io.open (filename [, mode])}

This function opens a file,
in the mode specified in the string @T{mode}.
It returns a new file handle,
or, in case of errors, @nil plus an error message.

The @T{mode} string can be any of the following:
@description{
@item{@Q{r}} read mode (the default);
@item{@Q{w}} write mode;
@item{@Q{a}} append mode;
@item{@Q{r+}} update mode, all previous data is preserved;
@item{@Q{w+}} update mode, all previous data is erased;
@item{@Q{a+}} append update mode, previous data is preserved,
  writing is only allowed at the end of file.
}
The @T{mode} string may also have a @T{b} at the end,
which is needed in some systems to open the file in binary mode.
This string is exactly what is used in the
@Nb{standard C} function @T{fopen}.

@LibEntry{io.output ([file])}

Similar to @T{io.input}, but operates over the default output file.

@LibEntry{io.popen ([prog [, mode]])}

Starts program @T{prog} in a separated process and returns
a file handle that you can use to read data from that program
(if @T{mode} is @T{"r"}, the default)
or to write data to that program
(if @T{mode} is @T{"w"}).

This function is system dependent and is not available
in all platforms.

@LibEntry{io.read (format1, @ldots)}

Equivalent to @T{io.input():read}.

@LibEntry{io.tmpfile ()}

Returns a handle for a temporary file.
This file is open in update mode
and it is automatically removed when the program ends.

@LibEntry{io.type (obj)}

Checks whether @T{obj} is a valid file handle.
Returns the string @T{"file"} if @T{obj} is an open file handle,
@T{"closed file"} if @T{obj} is a closed file handle,
and @nil if @T{obj} is not a file handle.

@LibEntry{io.write (value1, @ldots)}

Equivalent to @T{io.output():write}.



@LibEntry{file:close ()}

Closes @T{file}.
Note that files are automatically closed when garbage collected,
but that takes an unpredictable time to happen.

@label{flush: @LibEntry{file:flush ()}}

Saves any written data to @T{file}.

@LibEntry{file:lines ()}

Returns an iterator function that,
each time it is called,
returns a new line from the file.
Therefore, the construction
@verbatim{
       for line in file:lines() do ... end
}
will iterate over all lines of the file.
(Unlike @T{io.lines}, this function does not close the file
when the loop ends.)

@LibEntry{file:read (format1, @ldots)}

Reads the file @T{file},
according to the given formats, which specify what to read.
For each format,
the function returns a string (or a number) with the characters read,
or @nil if it cannot read data with the specified format.
When called without formats,
it uses a default format that reads the entire next line
(see below).

The available formats are
@description{
@item{@Q{*n}} reads a number;
this is the only format that returns a number instead of a string.
@item{@Q{*a}} reads the whole file, starting at the current position.
On end of file, it returns the empty string.
@item{@Q{*l}} reads the next line (skipping the end of line),
returning @nil on end of file.
This is the default format.
@item{@emph{number}} reads a string with up to that number of characters,
returning @nil on end of file.
If number is zero,
it reads nothing and returns an empty string,
or @nil on end of file.
}

@LibEntry{file:seek ([whence] [, offset])}

Sets and gets the file position,
measured from the beginning of the file,
to the position given by @T{offset} plus a base
specified by the string @T{whence}, as follows:
@description{
@item{@Q{set}} base is position 0 (beginning of the file);
@item{@Q{cur}} base is current position;
@item{@Q{end}} base is end of file;
}
In case of success, function @T{seek} returns the final file position,
measured in bytes from the beginning of the file.
If this function fails, it returns @nil,
plus a string describing the error.

The default value for @T{whence} is @T{"cur"},
and for @T{offset} is 0.
Therefore, the call @T{file:seek()} returns the current
file position, without changing it;
the call @T{file:seek("set")} sets the position to the
beginning of the file (and returns 0);
and the call @T{file:seek("end")} sets the position to the
end of the file, and returns its size.

@LibEntry{file:setvbuf (mode [, size])}

Sets the buffering mode for an output file.
There are three available modes:
@description{
@item{@Q{no}} no buffering; any output operation appear immediately.
@item{@Q{full}} full buffering; output operation is performed only
when the buffer is full (or when you @T{flush} the file @see{flush}).
@item{@Q{line}} line buffering; output is buffered until a newline is
output or there is any input from some special files
(such as a terminal device).
}
For the last two cases, @T{sizes}
specifies the size of the buffer, in bytes.
The default is an appropriate size.

@LibEntry{file:write (value1, @ldots)}

Writes the value of each of its arguments to
the filehandle @T{file}.
The arguments must be strings or numbers.
To write other values,
use @T{tostring} or @T{string.format} before @T{write}.


@label{libiosys: @subsection{Operating System Facilities}}

This library is implemented through table @IndexLIB{os}.

@LibEntry{os.clock ()}

Returns an approximation of the amount of CPU time
used by the program, in seconds.

@LibEntry{os.date ([format [, time]])}

Returns a string or a table containing date and time,
formatted according to the given string @T{format}.

If the @T{time} argument is present,
this is the time to be formatted
(see the @T{os.time} function for a description of this value).
Otherwise, @T{date} formats the current time.

If @T{format} starts with @Char{!},
then the date is formatted in Coordinated Universal Time.
After that optional character,
if @T{format} is @T{*t},
then @T{date} returns a table with the following fields:
@T{year} (four digits), @T{month} (1--12), @T{day} (1--31),
@T{hour} (0--23), @T{min} (0--59), @T{sec} (0--61),
@T{wday} (weekday, Sunday @Nb{is 1}),
@T{yday} (day of the year),
and @T{isdst} (daylight saving flag, a boolean).

If @T{format} is not @T{*t},
then @T{date} returns the date as a string,
formatted according to the same rules as the @Nb{C function} @T{strftime}.

When called without arguments,
@T{date} returns a reasonable date and time representation that depends on
the host system and on the current locale
(that is, @T{os.date()} is equivalent to @T{os.date("%c")}).

@LibEntry{os.difftime (t2, t1)}

Returns the number of seconds from time @T{t1} to time @T{t2}.
In Posix, Windows, and some other systems,
this value is exactly @T{t2}@Math{-}@T{t1}.

@LibEntry{os.execute (command)}

This function is equivalent to the @Nb{C function} @T{system}.
It passes @T{command} to be executed by an operating system shell.
It returns a status code, which is system-dependent.

@LibEntry{os.exit ([code])}

Calls the @Nb{C function} @T{exit},
with an optional @T{code},
to terminate the host program.
The default value for @T{code} is the success code.

@LibEntry{os.getenv (varname)}

Returns the value of the process environment variable @T{varname},
or @nil if the variable is not defined.

@LibEntry{os.remove (filename)}

Deletes the file with the given name.
If this function fails, it returns @nil,
plus a string describing the error.

@LibEntry{os.rename (oldname, newname)}

Renames file named @T{oldname} to @T{newname}.
If this function fails, it returns @nil,
plus a string describing the error.

@LibEntry{os.setlocale (locale [, category])}

Sets the current locale of the program.
@T{locale} is a string specifying a locale;
@T{category} is an optional string describing which category to change:
@T{"all"}, @T{"collate"}, @T{"ctype"},
@T{"monetary"}, @T{"numeric"}, or @T{"time"};
the default category is @T{"all"}.
The function returns the name of the new locale,
or @nil if the request cannot be honored.

@LibEntry{os.time ([table])}

Returns the current time when called without arguments,
or a time representing the date and time specified by the given table.
This table must have fields @T{year}, @T{month}, and @T{day},
and may have fields @T{hour}, @T{min}, @T{sec}, and @T{isdst}
(for a description of these fields, see the @T{os.date} function).

The returned value is a number, whose meaning depends on your system.
In Posix, Windows, and some other systems, this number counts the number
of seconds since some given start time (the @Q{epoch}).
In other systems, the meaning is not specified,
and the number returned by @T{time} can be used only as an argument to
@T{date} and @T{difftime}.

@LibEntry{os.tmpname ()}

Returns a string with a file name that can
be used for a temporary file.
The file must be explicitly opened before its use
and removed when no longer needed.


@label{libdebug: @subsection{The Reflexive Debug Interface}}

The @T{debug} library provides
the functionality of the debug interface to Lua programs.
You should exert care when using this library.
The functions provided here should be used exclusively for debugging
and similar tasks, such as profiling.
Please resist the temptation to use them as a
usual programming tool:
They can be very slow.
Moreover, several of its functions
violate some assumptions about Lua code
(e.g., that local variables cannot be accessed from outside or
that userdata metatables cannot be changed by Lua code)
and therefore can compromise some otherwise secure code.

All functions in this library are provided
inside a @IndexVerb{debug} table.


@LibEntry{debug.debug ()}

Enters an interactive mode with the user,
running each string that the user enters.
Using simple commands and other debug facilities,
the user can inspect global and local variables,
change their values, evaluate expressions, and so on.
A line containing only the word @T{cont} finishes this function,
so that the caller continues its execution.

Note that commands for @T{debug.debug} are not lexically nested
with any function, so they have no direct access to local variables.


@LibEntry{debug.getfenv (o)}
Returns the environment of object @T{o}.

@LibEntry{debug.gethook ()}

Returns the current hook settings, as three values:
the current hook function, the current hook mask,
and the current hook count
(as set by the @T{debug.sethook} function).


@LibEntry{debug.getinfo (function [, what])}

This function returns a table with information about a function.
You can give the function directly,
or you can give a number as the value of @T{function},
which means the function running at level @T{function} of the call stack:
Level 0 is the current function (@T{getinfo} itself);
level 1 is the function that called @T{getinfo};
and so on.
If @T{function} is a number larger than the number of active functions,
then @T{getinfo} returns @nil.

The returned table contains all the fields returned by @T{lua_getinfo},
with the string @T{what} describing which fields to fill in.
The default for @T{what} is to get all information available.
If present,
the option @Char{f}
adds a field named @T{func} with the function itself.

For instance, the expression @T{debug.getinfo(1,"n").name} returns
the name of the current function, if a reasonable name can be found,
and @T{debug.getinfo(print)} returns a table with all available information
about the @T{print} function.


@LibEntry{debug.getlocal (level, local)}

This function returns the name and the value of the local variable
with index @T{local} of the function at level @T{level} of the stack.
(The first parameter or local variable has @Nb{index 1}, and so on,
until the last active local variable.)
The function returns @nil if there is no local
variable with the given index,
and raises an error when called with a @T{level} out of range.
(You can call @T{debug.getinfo} to check whether the level is valid.)


@LibEntry{debug.getmetatable (object)}

If @T{object} does not have a metatable, returns @nil.
Otherwise, returns the metatable of the given object.

@LibEntry{debug.getupvalue (func, up)}

This function returns the name and the value of the upvalue
with index @T{up} of the function @T{func}.
The function returns @nil if there is no upvalue with the given index.


@LibEntry{debug.setfenv (o, table)}

Sets the environment of the given object.


@LibEntry{debug.sethook (hook, mask [, count])}

Sets the given function as a hook.
The string @T{mask} and the number @T{count} describe
when the hook will be called.
The string mask may have the following characters,
with the given meaning:
@description{
@item{@Tp{"c"}} The hook is called every time Lua calls a function;
@item{@Tp{"r"}} The hook is called every time Lua returns from a function;
@item{@Tp{"l"}} The hook is called every time Lua enters a new line of code.
}
With a @T{count} different from zero,
the hook is called after every @T{count} instructions.

When called without arguments,
the @T{debug.sethook} function turns off the hook.

When the hook is called, its first parameter is always a string
describing the event that triggered its call:
@T{"call"}, @T{"return"} (or @T{"tail return"}),
@T{"line"}, and @T{"count"}.
Moreover, for line events,
it also gets as its second parameter the new line number.
Inside a hook,
you can call @T{getinfo} with level 2 to get more information about
the running function
(@Nb{level 0} is the @T{getinfo} function,
and @Nb{level 1} is the hook function),
unless the event is @T{"tail return"}.
In this case, Lua is only simulating the return,
and a call to @T{getinfo} will return invalid data.


@LibEntry{debug.setlocal (level, local, value)}

This function assigns the value @T{value} to the local variable
with index @T{local} of the function at level @T{level} of the stack.
The function returns @nil if there is no local
variable with the given index,
and raises an error when called with a @T{level} out of range.
(You can call @T{getinfo} to check whether the level is valid.)
Otherwise, it returns the name of the local variable.


@LibEntry{debug.setmetatable (o, metatable)}

Sets the metatable for the given object.

@LibEntry{debug.setupvalue (func, up, value)}

This function assigns the value @T{value} to the upvalue
with index @T{up} of the function @T{func}.
The function returns @nil if there is no upvalue
with the given index.
Otherwise, it returns the name of the upvalue.

@LibEntry{debug.traceback ([message])}

Returns a string with a traceback of the call stack.
An optional @T{message} string is appended
at the beginning of the traceback. 
This function is typically used with @T{xpcall} to produce
better error messages.


