@label{lua-sa: @section{@Index{Lua Stand-alone}}}

Although Lua has been designed as an extension language,
to be embedded in a host @Nb{C program},
it is also frequently used as a stand-alone language.
An interpreter for Lua as a stand-alone language,
called simply @T{lua},
is provided with the standard distribution.
The stand-alone interpreter includes
all standard libraries plus the reflexive debug interface.
Its usage is:
@verbatim{
      lua [options] [script [args]]
}
The options are:
@description{
@item{@Tp{-} } executes @T{stdin} as a file;
@item{@Tp{-e} @emph{stat}} executes string @emph{stat};
@item{@Tp{-l} @emph{mod}} @Q{requires} @emph{mod};
@item{@Tp{-i}} enters interactive mode after running @emph{script};
@item{@Tp{-v}} prints version information;
@item{@Tp{-w}} traps accesses to undefined variables;
@item{@Tp{--}} stop handling options.
}
After handling its options, @T{lua} runs the given @emph{script},
passing to it the given @emph{args}.
When called without arguments,
@T{lua} behaves as @T{lua -v -i} when @T{stdin} is a terminal,
and as @T{lua -} otherwise.

Before running any argument,
the interpreter checks for an environment variable @IndexVerb{LUA_INIT}.
If its format is @At@emph{filename},
then lua executes the file.
Otherwise, lua executes the string itself.

All options are handled in order, except @T{-i}.
For instance, an invocation like
@verbatim{
       $ lua -e'a=1' -e 'print(a)' script.lua
}
will first set @T{a} to 1, then print @T{a},
and finally run the file @T{script.lua}.
(Here @T{$} is the shell prompt. Your prompt may be different.)

Before starting to run the script,
@T{lua} collects all arguments in the command line
in a global table called @T{arg}.
The script name is stored in index 0,
the first argument after the script name goes to index 1,
and so on.
Any arguments before the script name
(that is, the interpreter name plus the options)
go to negative indices.
For instance, in the call
@verbatim{
       $ lua -la.lua b.lua t1 t2
}
the interpreter first runs the file @T{a.lua},
then creates a table
@verbatim{
       arg = { [-2] = "lua", [-1] = "-la.lua", [0] = "b.lua",
               [1] = "t1", [2] = "t2" }
}
and finally runs the file @T{b.lua}.
The script is called with @T{arg[1]}, @T{arg[2]}, @ldots{}
as aguments;
it can acess those arguments with the vararg expression @T{...}.

In interactive mode,
if you write an incomplete statement,
the interpreter waits for its completion.

If the global variable @IndexVerb{_PROMPT} is defined as a string,
then its value is used as the prompt.
Therefore, the prompt can be changed directly on the command line:
@verbatim{
       $ lua -e"_PROMPT='myprompt> '" -i
}
(the outer pair of quotes is for the shell,
the inner is for Lua),
or in any Lua programs by assigning to @T{_PROMPT}.
Note the use of @T{-i} to enter interactive mode; otherwise,
the program would end just after the assignment to @T{_PROMPT}.

To allow the use of Lua as a
script interpreter in Unix systems,
the stand-alone interpreter skips
the first line of a chunk if it starts with @T{#}.
Therefore, Lua scripts can be made into executable programs
by using @T{chmod +x} and @Nb{the @T{#!}} form,
as in
@verbatim{
#!/usr/local/bin/lua
}
(Of course,
the location of the Lua interpreter may be different in your machine.
If @T{lua} is in your @T{PATH},
then 
@verbatim{
#!/usr/bin/env lua
}
is a more portable solution.) 

